summary.seg: The manuscript contains 24 treatises from the Hippocratic corpus. Although considered the most famous physician of Greek antiquity, and the founder of scientific medicine in Greece, very little is known about Hippocrates (ca. 460-370 BCE). The Hippocratic corpus comprises about 70 medical works, but in the opinion of scholars none can be confidently attributed to him.

The manuscript was copied in the first half of the 16th century by a still anonymous scribe, who copied also, for example, MS Par. Suppl. gr. 195. On the basis of the nature of the text copied in the manuscript, some scholars have placed its copy after 1538 (see Origin for details). Since the texts contain some lessons from the Basel printed edition of Hippocrates by Janus Cornarius of 1538, this date should be taken as terminus post quem for the copy (see Rivier 1962, pp. 136-137; Ecca 2016, p. 63).

support.material:
Western paper, folded in folio. Watermarks:
ff. 1-199, 200, 204-205, 209 Anchor in a circle, surmounted by a six-point star ( 65 45 ), in the centre of the leaf, comparable to Harlfinger Ancre 11 , which is dated to 1504.
ff. 201-203, 206-208 Crossbow in a circle ( 50 45 ), in the centre of the leaf, comparable to Sosower Arbalète 3 , which is dated in the beginning of th 16th c., and to Harlfinger Arbalète 51 , which is dated in 1509.
ff. 210-239 Anchor ( 55 43 ), in the centre of the leaf, comparable to Briquet Ancre 447 , which is dated in 1520.
ff. [III]-[IV] Cardinal's hat with countermark 3 A b (?) ( 45 45 ), in the centre of the leaf, comparable to Briquet Chapeau 3509 , which is dated to 1517.
f. [I] Scale with triangular plates, surmounted by a star (?), in the centre of the leaf, the watermark is only partially visible.

foliation.p: Foliation in brown ink in the upper margin, right, from 1 to 239: [I]-II + 1-239 + [III]-[IV]

collation.catchwords: Vertical catchwords by the scribe in the lower margin, near the gutter, written from the top down.

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript is in fair condition. Throughout the manuscript there are some dark and humidity stains.

layoutDesc.layout:
ff. 1r-239v A single column of 30 lines.
215 120

handNote.p:
ff. 1r-239v Hand A: the texts have been copied by a single scribe in a minuscule script datable to the first half of the 16th c. The scribe does not write iota subscript. The hand is the same as that which wrote
Paris, Bibliothèque Nationale de France, Suppl. gr. 195 . Gärtner (2015, p. 59) identifies the same hand in another manuscript of Hippocrates, Leiden, Bibliotheek der Rijksuniversiteit, Voss. gr. F° 53 (it was not possible to verify this identification).
The text is written in a brown ink, titles and initials in red.
Hand a: passim in the margins there are a few annotations in brown ink by John Caius, see e.g. ff. 160r, 199v.

decoDesc.decoNote:
Simple friezes in red ink precede some of the texts:
ff. 199v, 222r, 234v repeating pattern of undulating lines
f. 211r rope motif
f. 236r a single line
Thick red ink initials sometimes very simply decorated, see e.g. f. 6v. Blank space for larger initials has been left, e.g. on f. 1r.

additions.p: On f. [I] verso there is a table of the manuscript's contents written by John Caius, with references to the manuscript's foliation.
On f. II recto there is a note concerning John Caius' donation of the manuscript to the College.
On f. II recto and in the upper margin of f. 1r is written the number 4.

binding.p:
Modern western binding. Wooden boards; leather on spine and a third of the boards. The leather, which has been reused from the previous binding, shows a blind tooled geometrical decoration with rhombuses and small flowers. On the spine are pasted two paper labels with the two shelfmarks 27 (in red) and 50 (in black).
347 220 ca. 60

accMat.p: On ff. [I] recto and [IV] verso are pasted two parchment strips from a manuscript in Latin ( James 1907, dates it in the 14th c. in Italy).

provenance.p: The manuscript was owned by John Caius (1510-1573) Caius, John, 1510-1573 .

history.acquisition:
The manuscript was donated to the College Library by John Caius Caius, John, 1510-1573
(see note on f. II recto: Collegio suo de Goneville | et Caius in Canta|brigia, Joannes Caius | dono dedit). On the left board's interior is pasted the Gonville and Caius College bookplate (with handwritten shelfmarks in red, 27, and black 50).

recordHist.source: Description (2021) draws partly on M.R. James, A descriptive catalogue of the Manuscripts in the Library of Gonville and Caius College, vol. 1, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 1907, pp. 41-43.

availability.p: Visitors to Gonville and Caius College who wish to consult Lower Library material are required to apply to the Library in advance of their visit. For information on eligibility and admission procedures see: Gonville and Caius College: Library Information.
